sec.p:
Total genomic DNA was extracted from ethanol-fixed specimens of Amathia reptopinnata n. sp. from Oki Island and Matsushima, using a DNeasy Blood and Tissue Kit (Qiagen), following the manufacturer’s protocol. The 16S fragment was amplified with primer set 16Sar/16Sbr (
Palumbi et al . 1991
). The COI fragment was amplified with the primer pair LCO1490/HCO2198 (
Folmer et al . 1994
). PCR reactions were performed with ExTaq (TaKaRa). Conditions for hot-start thermal cycling were 4 min at 94° C; 40 cycles of 30 sec at 94° C, 30 sec at 48/52° C (16S/ COI), and 90 sec at 72° C; and 7 min at 72° C. PCR products were visualized on a 1% agarose gel and purified according to the method of
Boom et al . (1990)
with some modifications ( Kobayashi & Tachi 2009 ; Kobayashi et al . 2009). Cycle sequencing was performed with BigDye Terminator 3.1 (Life Technologies). Both product strands were sequenced with an ABI 3130 Genetic Analyzer (Life Technologies). Chromatograms were edited and overlapping sequence fragments were assembled using MEGA6.06 (
Tamura et al . 2013
). The sequences have been deposited with DDBJ/EMBL/GenBank under accession numbers LC512453 to LC512455 for Amathia reptopinnata n. sp. from Oki Island and Matsushima, respectively ( Table 1 ).

The 16S and COI sequences obtained for Amathia reptopinnata n. sp. were aligned with those from other bryozoans deposited in GenBank ( Table 1 ) using Clustal W (
Thompson et al . 1994
) implemented in MEGA6.06 (
Tamura et al . 2013
). The alignment was performed gene by gene. Most of the sites for both 16S and COI were unambiguously aligned. We therefore used the entire region, excluding gap sites, for our phylogenetic analyses. For the COI dataset, we tested the substitution saturation at 1st + 2nd and 3rd codon positions with DAMBE (
Xia et al . 2003
), with only fully resolved sites.

Maximum likelihood (ML) analyses were performed with MEGA 6.06. The best-fit model for the 16S and COI sequences determined by the AICc implemented in MEGA 6.06 were GTR+G (general time reversible [
Tavaré 1986
] with gamma-distributed rates) and GTR+G+I (general time reversible [
Tavaré 1986
] with gamma-distributed rates and invariant rates among sites), respectively. We also analysed the 16S and COI sequences as a concatenated data set; the best-fit model for the 16S + COI data set determined by the AICc implemented in MEGA 6.06 was GTR+G+I. Optimal ML trees were found by a tree-bisection reconnection (
TBR
) search, starting with a tree topology generated by the BIONJ method (
Gascuel 1997
) using maximum composite likelihood (MCL) distances (

Tamura 
et al
. 2004

). One-thousand bootstrap pseudoreplicates were analysed to obtain nodal support values.

